B3(a) — Train-Test Split & Evaluation
Since the data is time-based (monthly data over 3 years), I would split it based on time, not randomly.
Use the first ~80% (earlier months) as training data
Use the last ~20% (recent months) as test data
This way, the model learns from past data and is tested on future data, which matches real-world usage.


B3(b) — Explaining Different Recommendations (4 marks)
The model gives different recommendations for December and March because the input features change across months.
To investigate this, I would use feature importance from the model.
Steps:
1.Check which features are most important (e.g., month, festival, footfall, promotion type)
2.See how these features differ between December and March
Example explanation to marketing team:
December may have festivals and higher demand → Loyalty Points works better
March may have lower demand → Flat Discount attracts more customers
So the model is not random — it is adjusting based on seasonality and store conditions.

